# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: optical-character-recognition
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] The scientific discipline of computer vision is concerned with the theory behind artificial systems that extract information from images.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Image data can take many forms, such as video sequences, views from multiple cameras, multi-dimensional data from a 3D scanner, 3D point clouds from LiDaR sensors, or medical scanning devices.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] The technological discipline of computer vision seeks to apply its theories and models to the construction of computer vision systems.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Subdisciplines of computer vision include scene reconstruction, object detection, event detection, activity recognition, video tracking, object recognition, 3D pose estimation, learning, indexing, motion estimation, visual servoing, 3D scene modeling, and image restoration.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Computer vision is an interdisciplinary field that deals with how computers can be made to gain high-level understanding from digital images or videos.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] From the perspective of engineering, it seeks to automate tasks that the human visual system can do.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] "Computer vision is concerned with the automatic extraction, analysis, and understanding of useful information from a single image or a sequence of images.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] It involves the development of a theoretical and algorithmic basis to achieve automatic visual understanding." As a scientific discipline, computer vision is concerned with the theory behind artificial systems that extract information from images.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] The image data can take many forms, such as video sequences, views from multiple cameras, or multi-dimensional data from a medical scanner.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] As a technological discipline, computer vision seeks to apply its theories and models for the construction of computer vision systems.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Machine vision refers to a systems engineering discipline, especially in the context of factory automation.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] In more recent times, the terms computer vision and machine vision have converged to a greater degree.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] In the late 1960s, computer vision began at universities that were pioneering artificial intelligence.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] It was meant to mimic the human visual system as a stepping stone to endowing robots with intelligent behavior.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] In 1966, it was believed that this could be achieved through an undergraduate summer project, by attaching a camera to a computer and having it "describe what it saw".
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] What distinguished computer vision from the prevalent field of digital image processing at that time was a desire to extract three-dimensional structure from images with the goal of achieving full scene understanding.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] The next decade saw studies based on more rigorous mathematical analysis and quantitative aspects of computer vision.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] These include the concept of scale-space, the inference of shape from various cues such as shading, texture and focus, and contour models known as snakes.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Researchers also realized that many of these mathematical concepts could be treated within the same optimization framework as regularization and Markov random fields.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] By the 1990s, some of the previous research topics became more active than others.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Research in projective 3-D reconstructions led to better understanding of camera calibration.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] With the advent of optimization methods for camera calibration, it was realized that a lot of the ideas were already explored in bundle adjustment theory from the field of photogrammetry.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] This led to methods for sparse 3-D reconstructions of scenes from multiple images.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Progress was made on the dense stereo correspondence problem and further multi-view stereo techniques.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] At the same time, variations of graph cut were used to solve image segmentation.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] This decade also marked the first time statistical learning techniques were used in practice to recognize faces in images (see Eigenface).
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Toward the end of the 1990s, a significant change came about with the increased interaction between the fields of computer graphics and computer vision.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] This included image-based rendering, image morphing, view interpolation, panoramic image stitching and early light-field rendering.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Recent work has seen the resurgence of feature-based methods used in conjunction with machine learning techniques and complex optimization frameworks.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] The advancement of Deep Learning techniques has brought further life to the field of computer vision.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] The accuracy of deep learning algorithms on several benchmark computer vision data sets for tasks ranging from classification, segmentation and optical flow has surpassed prior methods.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Solid-state physics is another field that is closely related to computer vision.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Most computer vision systems rely on image sensors, which detect electromagnetic radiation, which is typically in the form of either visible, infrared or ultraviolet light.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] The sensors are designed using quantum physics.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] The process by which light interacts with surfaces is explained using physics.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Physics explains the behavior of optics which are a core part of most imaging systems.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Sophisticated image sensors even require quantum mechanics to provide a complete understanding of the image formation process.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Also, various measurement problems in physics can be addressed using computer vision, for example, motion in fluids.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] The starfish match with a ringed texture and a star outline, whereas most sea urchins match with a striped texture and oval shape.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] However, the instance of a ring-textured sea urchin creates a weakly weighted association between them.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] The network correctly detects the starfish.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] However, the weakly weighted association between ringed texture and sea urchin also confers a weak signal to the latter from one of two intermediate nodes.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] In addition, a shell that was not included in the training gives a weak signal for the oval shape, also resulting in a weak signal for the sea urchin output.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] In reality, textures and outlines would not be represented by single nodes, but rather by associated weight patterns of multiple nodes.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Neurobiology has greatly influenced the development of computer vision algorithms.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Over the last century, there has been an extensive study of eyes, neurons, and brain structures devoted to the processing of visual stimuli in both humans and various animals.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] This has led to a coarse yet convoluted description of how natural vision systems operate in order to solve certain vision-related tasks.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] These results have led to a sub-field within computer vision where artificial systems are designed to mimic the processing and behavior of biological systems at different levels of complexity.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Also, some of the learning-based methods developed within computer vision (*e.g.* neural net and deep learning based image and feature analysis and classification) have their background in neurobiology.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] The Neocognitron, a neural network developed in the 1970s by Kunihiko Fukushima, is an early example of computer vision taking direct inspiration from neurobiology, specifically the primary visual cortex.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Some strands of computer vision research are closely related to the study of biological vision—indeed, just as many strands of AI research are closely tied with research into human intelligence and the use of stored knowledge to interpret, integrate, and utilize visual information.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] The field of biological vision studies and models the physiological processes behind visual perception in humans and other animals.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Computer vision, on the other hand, develops and describes the algorithms implemented in software and hardware behind artificial vision systems.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] An interdisciplinary exchange between biological and computer vision has proven fruitful for both fields.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Yet another field related to computer vision is signal processing.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Many methods for processing one-variable signals, typically temporal signals, can be extended in a natural way to the processing of two-variable signals or multi-variable signals in computer vision.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] However, because of the specific nature of images, there are many methods developed within computer vision that have no counterpart in the processing of one-variable signals.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Together with the multi-dimensionality of the signal, this defines a subfield in signal processing as a part of computer vision.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Robot navigation sometimes deals with autonomous path planning or deliberation for robotic systems to navigate through an environment.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] A detailed understanding of these environments is required to navigate through them.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Visual computing is a generic term for all computer science disciplines dealing with images and 3D models, such as computer graphics, image processing, visualization, computer vision, virtual and augmented reality, video processing, and computational visualistics.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Visual computing also includes aspects of pattern recognition, human computer interaction, machine learning and digital libraries.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] The core challenges are the acquisition, processing, analysis and rendering of visual information (mainly images and video).
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Application areas include industrial quality control, medical image processing and visualization, surveying, robotics, multimedia systems, virtual heritage, special effects in movies and television, and ludology.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Visual computing also includes digital art and digital media studies.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Besides the above-mentioned views on computer vision, many of the related research topics can also be studied from a purely mathematical point of view.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] For example, many methods in computer vision are based on statistics, optimization or geometry.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Finally, a significant part of the field is devoted to the implementation aspect of computer vision; how existing methods can be realized in various combinations of software and hardware, or how these methods can be modified in order to gain processing speed without losing too much performance.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Computer vision is also used in fashion eCommerce, inventory management, patent search, furniture, and the beauty industry.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] The fields most closely related to computer vision are image processing, image analysis and machine vision.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] There is a significant overlap in the range of techniques and applications that these cover.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] This implies that the basic techniques that are used and developed in these fields are similar, something which can be interpreted as there is only one field with different names.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] In image processing, the input and output are both images, whereas in computer vision, the input is an image or video, and the output could be an enhanced image, an analysis of the image's content, or even a system's behavior based on that analysis.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Computer graphics produces image data from 3D models, and computer vision often produces 3D models from image data.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] There is also a trend towards a combination of the two disciplines, *e.g.*, as explored in augmented reality.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Photogrammetry also overlaps with computer vision, e.g., stereophotogrammetry vs. computer stereo vision.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Applications range from tasks such as industrial machine vision systems which, say, inspect bottles speeding by on a production line, to research into artificial intelligence and computers or robots that can comprehend the world around them.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] The computer vision and machine vision fields have significant overlap.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Computer vision covers the core technology of automated image analysis which is used in many fields.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Machine vision usually refers to a process of combining automated image analysis with other methods and technologies to provide automated inspection and robot guidance in industrial applications.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] In many computer-vision applications, computers are pre-programmed to solve a particular task, but methods based on learning are now becoming increasingly common.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] For 2024, the leading areas of computer vision were industry (market size US$5.22 billion), medicine (market size US$2.6 billion), military (market size US$996.2 million).
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] One of the most prominent application fields is medical computer vision, or medical image processing, characterized by the extraction of information from image data to diagnose a patient.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] An example of this is the detection of tumours, arteriosclerosis or other malign changes, and a variety of dental pathologies; measurements of organ dimensions, blood flow, etc. are another example.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] It also supports medical research by providing new information: *e.g.*, about the structure of the brain or the quality of medical treatments.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Applications of computer vision in the medical area also include enhancement of images interpreted by humans—ultrasonic images or X-ray images, for example—to reduce the influence of noise.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] A second application area in computer vision is in industry, sometimes called machine vision, where information is extracted for the purpose of supporting a production process.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] One example is quality control where details or final products are being automatically inspected in order to find defects.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] One of the most prevalent fields for such inspecti is the Wafer industry in which every single Wafer is being measured and inspected for inaccuracies or defects to prevent a computer chip from coming to market in an unusable manner.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Another example is a measurement of the position and orientation of details to be picked up by a robot arm.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Machine vision is also heavily used in the agricultural processes to remove undesirable foodstuff from bulk material, a process called optical sorting.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] The obvious examples are the detection of enemy soldiers or vehicles and missile guidance.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] More advanced systems for missile guidance send the missile to an area rather than a specific target, and target selection is made when the missile reaches the area based on locally acquired image data.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Modern military concepts, such as "battlefield awareness", imply that various sensors, including image sensors, provide a rich set of information about a combat scene that can be used to support strategic decisions.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] In this case, automatic processing of the data is used to reduce complexity and to fuse information from multiple sensors to increase reliability.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] One of the newer application areas is autonomous vehicles, which include submersibles, land-based vehicles (small robots with wheels, cars, or trucks), aerial vehicles, and unmanned aerial vehicles (UAV).
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] The level of autonomy ranges from fully autonomous (unmanned) vehicles to vehicles where computer-vision-based systems support a driver or a pilot in various situations.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Fully autonomous vehicles typically use computer vision for navigation, e.g., for knowing where they are or mapping their environment (SLAM), for detecting obstacles.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] It can also be used for detecting certain task-specific events, *e.g.*, a UAV looking for forest fires.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Examples of supporting systems are obstacle warning systems in cars, cameras and LiDAR sensors in vehicles, and systems for autonomous landing of aircraft.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Several car manufacturers have demonstrated systems for autonomous driving of cars.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] There are ample examples of military autonomous vehicles ranging from advanced missiles to UAVs for recon missions or missile guidance.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Space exploration is already being made with autonomous vehicles using computer vision, *e.g.*, NASA's *Curiosity* and CNSA's *Yutu-2* rover.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Materials such as rubber and silicon are being used to create sensors that allow for applications such as detecting microundulations and calibrating robotic hands.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Rubber can be used in order to create a mold that can be placed over a finger, inside of this mold would be multiple strain gauges.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] The finger mold and sensors could then be placed on top of a small sheet of rubber containing an array of rubber pins.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] A user can then wear the finger mold and trace a surface.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] A computer can then read the data from the strain gauges and measure if one or more of the pins are being pushed upward.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] If a pin is being pushed upward then the computer can recognize this as an imperfection in the surface.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] This sort of technology is useful in order to receive accurate data on imperfections on a very large surface.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Another variation of this finger mold sensor are sensors that contain a camera suspended in silicon.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] The silicon forms a dome around the outside of the camera and embedded in the silicon are point markers that are equally spaced.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] These cameras can then be placed on devices such as robotic hands in order to allow the computer to receive highly accurate tactile data.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Each of the application areas described above employ a range of computer vision tasks; more or less well-defined measurement problems or processing problems, which can be solved using a variety of methods.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Some examples of typical computer vision tasks are presented below.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Computer vision tasks include methods for acquiring, processing, analyzing and understanding digital images, and extraction of high-dimensional data from the real world in order to produce numerical or symbolic information, *e.g.*, in the forms of decisions.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Understanding in this context means the transformation of visual images into descriptions of the world that can interface with other thought processes and elicit appropriate action.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] This image understanding can be seen as the disentangling of symbolic information from image data using models constructed with the aid of geometry, physics, statistics, and learning theory.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] The classical problem in computer vision, image processing, and machine vision is that of determining whether or not the image data contains some specific object, feature, or activity.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Different varieties of recognition problem are described in the literature.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Currently, the best algorithms for such tasks are based on convolutional neural networks.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] An illustration of their capabilities is given by the ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge; this is a benchmark in object classification and detection, with millions of images and 1000 object classes used in the competition.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Performance of convolutional neural networks on the ImageNet tests is now close to that of humans.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] The best algorithms still struggle with objects that are small or thin, such as a small ant on the stem of a flower or a person holding a quill in their hand.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] They also have trouble with images that have been distorted with filters (an increasingly common phenomenon with modern digital cameras).
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] By contrast, those kinds of images rarely trouble humans.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Humans, however, tend to have trouble with other issues.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] For example, they are not good at classifying objects into fine-grained classes, such as the particular breed of dog or species of bird, whereas convolutional neural networks handle this with ease.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Several tasks relate to motion estimation, where an image sequence is processed to produce an estimate of the velocity either at each points in the image or in the 3D scene or even of the camera that produces the images.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Given one or (typically) more images of a scene, or a video, scene reconstruction aims at computing a 3D model of the scene.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] In the simplest case, the model can be a set of 3D points.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] More sophisticated methods produce a complete 3D surface model.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] The advent of 3D imaging not requiring motion or scanning, and related processing algorithms is enabling rapid advances in this field.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Grid-based 3D sensing can be used to acquire 3D images from multiple angles.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Algorithms are now available to stitch multiple 3D images together into point clouds and 3D models.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Image restoration comes into the picture when the original image is degraded or damaged due to some external factors like lens wrong positioning, transmission interference, low lighting or motion blurs, etc., which is referred to as noise.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] When the images are degraded or damaged, the information to be extracted from them also gets damaged.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Therefore, we need to recover or restore the image as it was intended to be.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] The aim of image restoration is the removal of noise (sensor noise, motion blur, etc.) from images.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] The simplest possible approach for noise removal is various types of filters, such as low-pass filters or median filters.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] More sophisticated methods assume a model of how the local image structures look to distinguish them from noise.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] By first analyzing the image data in terms of the local image structures, such as lines or edges, and then controlling the filtering based on local information from the analysis step, a better level of noise removal is usually obtained compared to the simpler approaches.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] The organization of a computer vision system is highly application-dependent.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Some systems are stand-alone applications that solve a specific measurement or detection problem, while others constitute a sub-system of a larger design which, for example, also contains sub-systems for control of mechanical actuators, planning, information databases, man-machine interfaces, etc.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] The specific implementation of a computer vision system also depends on whether its functionality is pre-specified or if some part of it can be learned or modified during operation.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Many functions are unique to the application.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] There are, however, typical functions that are found in many computer vision systems.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] More complex features may be related to texture, shape, or motion.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Image-understanding systems (IUS) include three levels of abstraction as follows: low level includes image primitives such as edges, texture elements, or regions; intermediate level includes boundaries, surfaces and volumes; and high level includes objects, scenes, or events.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Many of these requirements are entirely topics for further research.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] The representational requirements in the designing of IUS for these levels are: representation of prototypical concepts, concept organization, spatial knowledge, temporal knowledge, scaling, and description by comparison and differentiation.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] While inference refers to the process of deriving new, not explicitly represented facts from currently known facts, control refers to the process that selects which of the many inference, search, and matching techniques should be applied at a particular stage of processing.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Inference and control requirements for IUS are: search and hypothesis activation, matching and hypothesis testing, generation and use of expectations, change and focus of attention, certainty and strength of belief, inference and goal satisfaction.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] There are many kinds of computer vision systems; however, all of them contain these basic elements: a power source, at least one image acquisition device (camera, ccd, etc.), a processor, and control and communication cables or some kind of wireless interconnection mechanism.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] In addition, a practical vision system contains software, as well as a display in order to monitor the system.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Vision systems for inner spaces, as most industrial ones, contain an illumination system and may be placed in a controlled environment.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Furthermore, a completed system includes many accessories, such as camera supports, cables, and connectors.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Most computer vision systems use visible-light cameras passively viewing a scene at frame rates of at most 60 frames per second (usually far slower).
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Such hardware captures "images" that are then processed often using the same computer vision algorithms used to process visible-light images.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] For applications in robotics, fast, real-time video systems are critically important and often can simplify the processing needed for certain algorithms.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] When combined with a high-speed projector, fast image acquisition allows 3D measurement and feature tracking to be realized.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] Egocentric vision systems are composed of a wearable camera that automatically take pictures from a first-person perspective.
[src:optical-character-recognition/computer-vision] As of 2016, vision processing units are emerging as a new class of processors to complement CPUs and graphics processing units (GPUs) in this role.
[src:optical-character-recognition/connectionist-temporal-classification] The input is a sequence of observations, and the outputs are a sequence of labels, which can include blank outputs.
[src:optical-character-recognition/connectionist-temporal-classification] The difficulty of training comes from there being many more observations than there are labels.
[src:optical-character-recognition/connectionist-temporal-classification] For example, in speech audio there can be multiple time slices which correspond to a single phoneme.
[src:optical-character-recognition/connectionist-temporal-classification] Since we don't know the alignment of the observed sequence with the target labels we predict a probability distribution at each time step.
[src:optical-character-recognition/connectionist-temporal-classification] A CTC network has a continuous output (e.g. softmax), which is fitted through training to model the probability of a label.
[src:optical-character-recognition/connectionist-temporal-classification] CTC does not attempt to learn boundaries and timings: Label sequences are considered equivalent if they differ only in alignment, ignoring blanks.
[src:optical-character-recognition/connectionist-temporal-classification] Equivalent label sequences can occur in many ways – which makes scoring a non-trivial task, but there is an efficient forward–backward algorithm for that.
[src:optical-character-recognition/connectionist-temporal-classification] CTC scores can then be used with the back-propagation algorithm to update the neural network weights.
[src:optical-character-recognition/connectionist-temporal-classification] Alternative approaches to a CTC-fitted neural network include a hidden Markov model (HMM).
[src:optical-character-recognition/connectionist-temporal-classification] In 2009, a Connectionist Temporal Classification (CTC)-trained LSTM network was the first RNN to win pattern recognition contests when it won several competitions in connected handwriting recognition.
[src:optical-character-recognition/connectionist-temporal-classification] In 2014, the Chinese company Baidu used a bidirectional RNN (not an LSTM) trained on the CTC loss function to break the 2S09 Switchboard Hub5'00 speech recognition dataset benchmark without using any traditional speech processing methods.
[src:optical-character-recognition/connectionist-temporal-classification] In 2015, it was used in Google voice search and dictation on Android devices.
[src:optical-character-recognition/connectionist-temporal-classification] CTC is limited to monotonic alignment, which is not a problem for voice recognition, but may be a problem for language translation, as later words in a language A may correspond to earlier words in language B, since the word ordering is different for different languages.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A **convolutional neural network** (**CNN**) is a type of feedforward neural network that learns features via filter (or kernel) optimization.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This type of deep learning network has been applied to process and make predictions from many different types of data including text, images and audio.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs are the de-facto standard in deep learning-based approaches to computer vision and image processing, and have only recently been replaced—in some cases—by newer architectures such as the transformer.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Vanishing gradients and exploding gradients, seen during backpropagation in earlier neural networks, are prevented by the regularization that comes from using shared weights over fewer connections.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, for *each* neuron in the fully-connected layer, 10,000 weights would be required for processing an image sized 100 × 100 pixels.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, applying cascaded *convolution* (or cross-correlation) kernels, only 25 weights for each convolutional layer are required to process 5x5-sized tiles.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Higher-layer features are extracted from wider context windows, compared to lower-layer features.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs are also known as **shift invariant** or **space invariant artificial neural networks**, based on the shared-weight architecture of the convolution kernels or filters that slide along input features and provide translation-equivariant responses known as feature maps.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Counter-intuitively, most convolutional neural networks are not invariant to translation, due to the downsampling operation they apply to the input.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Feedforward neural networks are usually fully connected networks, that is, each neuron in one layer is connected to all neurons in the next layer.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The "full connectivity" of these networks makes them prone to overfitting data.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional networks were inspired by biological processes in that the connectivity pattern between neurons resembles the organization of the animal visual cortex.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Individual cortical neurons respond to stimuli only in a restricted region of the visual field known as the receptive field.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The receptive fields of different neurons partially overlap such that they cover the entire visual field.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs use relatively little pre-processing compared to other image classification algorithms.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This means that the network learns to optimize the filters (or kernels) through automated learning, whereas in traditional algorithms these filters are hand-engineered.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This simplifies and automates the process, enhancing efficiency and scalability overcoming human-intervention bottlenecks.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A convolutional neural network consists of an input layer, hidden layers and an output layer.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In a convolutional neural network, the hidden layers include one or more layers that perform convolutions.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Typically this includes a layer that performs a dot product of the convolution kernel with the layer's input matrix.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This product is usually the Frobenius inner product, and its activation function is commonly ReLU.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] As the convolution kernel slides along the input matrix for the layer, the convolution operation generates a feature map, which in turn contributes to the input of the next layer.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is followed by other layers such as pooling layers, fully connected layers, and normalization layers.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Here it should be noted how close a convolutional neural network is to a matched filter.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (number of inputs) × (feature map height) × (feature map width) × (feature map channels).
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional layers convolve the input and pass its result to the next layer.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is similar to the response of a neuron in the visual cortex to a specific stimulus.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each convolutional neuron processes data only for its receptive field.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Although fully connected feedforward neural networks can be used to learn features and classify data, this architecture is generally impractical for larger inputs (e.g., high-resolution images), which would require massive numbers of neurons because each pixel is a relevant input feature.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A fully connected layer for an image of size 100 × 100 has 10,000 weights for *each* neuron in the second layer.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolution reduces the number of free parameters, allowing the network to be deeper.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, using a 5 × 5 tiling region, each with the same shared weights, requires only 25 neurons.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Using shared weights means there are many fewer parameters, which helps avoid the vanishing gradients and exploding gradients problems seen during backpropagation in earlier neural networks.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] To speed processing, standard convolutional layers can be replaced by depthwise separable convolutional layers, which are based on a depthwise convolution followed by a pointwise convolution.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The *depthwise convolution* is a spatial convolution applied independently over each channel of the input tensor, while the *pointwise convolution* is a standard convolution restricted to the use of $1\times 1$ kernels.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional networks may include local and/or global pooling layers along with traditional convolutional layers.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Pooling layers reduce the dimensions of data by combining the outputs of neuron clusters at one layer into a single neuron in the next layer.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Local pooling combines small clusters, tiling sizes such as 2 × 2 are commonly used.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Global pooling acts on all the neurons of the feature map.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] There are two common types of pooling in popular use: max and average.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] *Max pooling* uses the maximum value of each local cluster of neurons in the feature map, while *average pooling* takes the average value.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Fully connected layers connect every neuron in one layer to every neuron in another layer.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is the same as a traditional multilayer perceptron neural network (MLP).
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each neuron in the fully connected layer receives input from all the neurons in the previous layer.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] These inputs are weighted and summed with the corresponding biases, and then passed through an activation function to perform a nonlinear transformation, generating the output.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The flattened matrix goes through a fully connected layer to classify the images.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In neural networks, each neuron receives input from some number of locations in the previous layer.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In a convolutional layer, each neuron receives input from only a restricted area of the previous layer called the neuron's *receptive field*.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Whereas, in a fully connected layer, the receptive field is the *entire previous layer*.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Thus, in each convolutional layer, each neuron takes input from a larger area in the input than previous layers.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is due to applying the convolution over and over, which takes the value of a pixel into account, as well as its surrounding pixels.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] When using dilated layers, the number of pixels in the receptive field remains constant, but the field is more sparsely populated as its dimensions grow when combining the effect of several layers.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] To manipulate the receptive field size as desired, there are some alternatives to the standard convolutional layer.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, atrous or dilated convolution expands the receptive field size without increasing the number of parameters by interleaving visible and blind regions.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Moreover, a single dilated convolutional layer can comprise filters with multiple dilation ratios, thus having a variable receptive field size.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each neuron in a neural network computes an output value by applying a specific function to the input values received from the receptive field in the previous layer.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The function that is applied to the input values is determined by a vector of weights and a bias (typically real numbers).
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Learning consists of iteratively adjusting these biases and weights.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The vectors of weights and biases are called *filters* and represent particular features of the input (e.g., a particular shape).
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A distinguishing feature of CNNs is that many neurons can share the same filter.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This reduces the memory footprint because a single bias and a single vector of weights are used across all receptive fields that share that filter, as opposed to each receptive field having its own bias and vector weighting.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A deconvolutional neural network is essentially the reverse of a CNN.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It consists of deconvolutional layers and unpooling layers.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A deconvolutional layer is the transpose of a convolutional layer.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Specifically, a convolutional layer can be written as a multiplication with a matrix, and a deconvolutional layer is multiplication with the transpose of that matrix.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The max-unpooling layer is the simplest, as it simply copies each entry multiple times.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, a 2-by-2 max-unpooling layer is $[x]\mapsto {\begin{bmatrix}x&x\\x&x\end{bmatrix}}$ .
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Deconvolution layers are used in image generators.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] By default, it creates periodic checkerboard artifact, which can be fixed by upscale-then-convolve.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNN are often compared to the way the brain achieves vision processing in living organisms.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Work by Hubel and Wiesel in the 1950s and 1960s showed that cat visual cortices contain neurons that individually respond to small regions of the visual field.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Provided the eyes are not moving, the region of visual space within which visual stimuli affect the firing of a single neuron is known as its receptive field.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Neighboring cells have similar and overlapping receptive fields.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Receptive field size and location varies systematically across the cortex to form a complete map of visual space.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The cortex in each hemisphere represents the contralateral visual field.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Hubel and Wiesel also proposed a cascading model of these two types of cells for use in pattern recognition tasks.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the same paper, Fukushima also introduced the ReLU (rectified linear unit) activation function.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The "neocognitron" was introduced by Fukushima in 1980.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Several supervised and unsupervised learning algorithms have been proposed over the decades to train the weights of a neocognitron.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Today, however, the CNN architecture is usually trained through backpropagation.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Fukushima's ReLU activation function was not used in his neocognitron since all the weights were nonnegative; lateral inhibition was used instead.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The rectifier has become a very popular activation function for CNNs and deep neural networks in general.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The term "convolution" first appears in neural networks in a paper by Toshiteru Homma, Les Atlas, and Robert Marks II at the first Conference on Neural Information Processing Systems in 1987.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their paper replaced multiplication with convolution in time, inherently providing shift invariance, motivated by and connecting more directly to the signal-processing concept of a filter, and demonstrated it on a speech recognition task.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] They also pointed out that as a data-trainable system, convolution is essentially equivalent to correlation since reversal of the weights does not affect the final learned function ("For convenience, we denote * as correlation instead of convolution.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Note that convolving a(t) with b(t) is equivalent to correlating a(-t) with b(t).").
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Modern CNN implementations typically do correlation and call it convolution, for convenience, as they did here.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The time delay neural network (TDNN) was introduced in 1987 by Alex Waibel et al. for phoneme recognition and was an early convolutional network exhibiting shift-invariance.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A TDNN is a 1-D convolutional neural net where the convolution is performed along the time axis of the data.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is the first CNN utilizing weight sharing in combination with a training by gradient descent, using backpropagation.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Thus, while also using a pyramidal structure as in the neocognitron, it performed a global optimization of the weights instead of a local one.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] TDNNs are convolutional networks that share weights along the temporal dimension.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] They allow speech signals to be processed time-invariantly.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 1990 Hampshire and Waibel introduced a variant that performs a two-dimensional convolution.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Since these TDNNs operated on spectrograms, the resulting phoneme recognition system was invariant to both time and frequency shifts, as with images processed by a neocognitron.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] TDNNs improved the performance of far-distance speech recognition.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (1989) designed a 2-D CNN system to recognize hand-written ZIP Code numbers.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, the lack of an efficient training method to determine the kernel coefficients of the involved convolutions meant that all the coefficients had to be laboriously hand-designed.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Following the advances in the training of 1-D CNNs by Waibel et al.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (1989) used back-propagation to learn the convolution kernel coefficients directly from images of hand-written numbers.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Learning was thus fully automatic, performed better than manual coefficient design, and was suited to a broader range of image recognition problems and image types.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (1988) used back-propagation to train the convolution kernels of a CNN for alphabets recognition.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The model was called shift-invariant pattern recognition neural network before the name CNN was coined later in the early 1990s.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Wei Zhang et al. also applied the same CNN without the last fully connected layer for medical image object segmentation (1991) and breast cancer detection in mammograms (1994).
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This approach became a foundation of modern computer vision.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 1990 Yamaguchi et al. introduced the concept of max pooling, a fixed filtering operation that calculates and propagates the maximum value of a given region.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] They did so by combining TDNNs with max pooling to realize a speaker-independent isolated word recognition system.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In their system they used several TDNNs per word, one for each syllable.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The results of each TDNN over the input signal were combined using max pooling and the outputs of the pooling layers were then passed on to networks performing the actual word classification.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In a variant of the neocognitron called the *cresceptron*, instead of using Fukushima's spatial averaging with inhibition and saturation, J.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Weng et al. in 1993 used max pooling, where a downsampling unit computes the maximum of the activations of the units in its patch, introducing this method into the vision field.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Max pooling is often used in modern CNNs.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] LeNet-5, a pioneering 7-level convolutional network by LeCun et al. in 1995, classifies hand-written numbers on checks digitized in 32×32 pixel images.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The ability to process higher-resolution images requires larger and more layers of convolutional neural networks, so this technique is constrained by the availability of computing resources.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It was superior than other commercial courtesy amount reading systems (as of 1995).
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The system was integrated in NCR's check reading systems, and fielded in several American banks since June 1996, reading millions of checks per day.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A shift-invariant neural network was proposed by Wei Zhang et al. for image character recognition in 1988.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is a modified Neocognitron by keeping only the convolutional interconnections between the image feature layers and the last fully connected layer.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The model was trained with back-propagation.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The training algorithm was further improved in 1991 to improve its generalization ability.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The model architecture was modified by removing the last fully connected layer and applied for medical image segmentation (1991) and automatic detection of breast cancer in mammograms (1994).
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A different convolution-based design was proposed in 1988 for application to decomposition of one-dimensional electromyography convolved signals via de-convolution.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This design was modified in 1989 to other de-convolution-based designs.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Although CNNs were invented in the 1980s, their breakthrough in the 2000s required fast implementations on graphics processing units (GPUs).
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Jung that standard neural networks can be greatly accelerated on GPUs.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their implementation was 20 times faster than an equivalent implementation on CPU.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2005, another paper also emphasised the value of GPGPU for machine learning.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The first GPU-implementation of a CNN was described in 2006 by K.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their implementation was 4 times faster than an equivalent implementation on CPU.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the same period, GPUs were also used for unsupervised training of deep belief networks.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2010, Dan Ciresan et al. at IDSIA trained deep feedforward networks on GPUs.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2011, they extended this to CNNs, accelerating by 60 compared to training CPU.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2011, the network won an image recognition contest where they achieved superhuman performance for the first time.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Then they won more competitions and achieved state of the art on several benchmarks.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Subsequently, AlexNet, a similar GPU-based CNN by Alex Krizhevsky et al. won the ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge 2012.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It was an early catalytic event for the AI boom.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Compared to the training of CNNs using GPUs, not much attention was given to CPU.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (Viebke et al 2019) parallelizes CNN by thread- and SIMD-level parallelism that is available on the Intel Xeon Phi.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the past, traditional multilayer perceptron (MLP) models were used for image recognition.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, the full connectivity between nodes caused the curse of dimensionality, and was computationally intractable with higher-resolution images.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A 1000×1000-pixel image with RGB color channels has 3 million weights per fully-connected neuron, which is too high to feasibly process efficiently at scale.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, in CIFAR-10, images are only of size 32×32×3 (32 wide, 32 high, 3 color channels), so a single fully connected neuron in the first hidden layer of a regular neural network would have 32*32*3 = 3,072 weights.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Also, such network architecture does not take into account the spatial structure of data, treating input pixels which are far apart in the same way as pixels that are close together.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This ignores locality of reference in data with a grid-topology (such as images), both computationally and semantically.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Thus, full connectivity of neurons is wasteful for purposes such as image recognition that are dominated by spatially local input patterns.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional neural networks are variants of multilayer perceptrons, designed to emulate the behavior of a visual cortex.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] These models mitigate the challenges posed by the MLP architecture by exploiting the strong spatially local correlation present in natural images.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Together, these properties allow CNNs to achieve better generalization on vision problems.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Weight sharing dramatically reduces the number of free parameters learned, thus lowering the memory requirements for running the network and allowing the training of larger, more powerful networks.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A CNN architecture is formed by a stack of distinct layers that transform the input volume into an output volume (e.g. holding the class scores) through a differentiable function.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A few distinct types of layers are commonly used.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The convolutional layer is the core building block of a CNN.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The layer's parameters consist of a set of learnable filters (or kernels), which have a small receptive field, but extend through the full depth of the input volume.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] During the forward pass, each filter is convolved across the width and height of the input volume, computing the dot product between the filter entries and the input, producing a 2-dimensional activation map of that filter.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] As a result, the network learns filters that activate when it detects some specific type of feature at some spatial position in the input.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Stacking the activation maps for all filters along the depth dimension forms the full output volume of the convolution layer.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Every entry in the output volume can thus also be interpreted as an output of a neuron that looks at a small region in the input.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each entry in an activation map use the same set of parameters that define the filter.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Self-supervised learning has been adapted for use in convolutional layers by using sparse patches with a high-mask ratio and a global response normalization layer.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] When dealing with high-dimensional inputs such as images, it is impractical to connect neurons to all neurons in the previous volume because such a network architecture does not take the spatial structure of the data into account.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional networks exploit spatially local correlation by enforcing a sparse local connectivity pattern between neurons of adjacent layers: each neuron is connected to only a small region of the input volume.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The extent of this connectivity is a hyperparameter called the receptive field of the neuron.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The connections are local in space (along width and height), but always extend along the entire depth of the input volume.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Such an architecture ensures that the learned filters produce the strongest response to a spatially local input pattern.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The spatial size of the output volume is a function of the input volume size W , the kernel field size K of the convolutional layer neurons, the stride S , and the amount of zero padding P on the border.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] If this number is not an integer, then the strides are incorrect and the neurons cannot be tiled to fit across the input volume in a symmetric way.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In general, setting zero padding to be ${\textstyle P=(K-1)/2}$ when the stride is $S=1$ ensures that the input volume and output volume will have the same size spatially.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, it is not always completely necessary to use all of the neurons of the previous layer.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, a neural network designer may decide to use just a portion of padding.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A parameter sharing scheme is used in convolutional layers to control the number of free parameters.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It relies on the assumption that if a patch feature is useful to compute at some spatial position, then it should also be useful to compute at other positions.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Denoting a single 2-dimensional slice of depth as a *depth slice*, the neurons in each depth slice are constrained to use the same weights and bias.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Since all neurons in a single depth slice share the same parameters, the forward pass in each depth slice of the convolutional layer can be computed as a convolution of the neuron's weights with the input volume.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Therefore, it is common to refer to the sets of weights as a filter (or a kernel), which is convolved with the input.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The result of this convolution is an activation map, and the set of activation maps for each different filter are stacked together along the depth dimension to produce the output volume.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Parameter sharing contributes to the translation invariance of the CNN architecture.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Sometimes, the parameter sharing assumption may not make sense.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is especially the case when the input images to a CNN have some specific centered structure; for which we expect completely different features to be learned on different spatial locations.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One practical example is when the inputs are faces that have been centered in the image: we might expect different eye-specific or hair-specific features to be learned in different parts of the image.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In that case it is common to relax the parameter sharing scheme, and instead simply call the layer a "locally connected layer".
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In this layer, the convolutional kernels' parameters are not shared.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Instead, the network learns independent weights and biases for each spatial location.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This allows each location to have its own feature-learning ability, making it better suited to handle images with distinct central structures or irregular features.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Another important concept of CNNs is pooling, which is used as a form of non-linear down-sampling.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Pooling provides downsampling because it reduces the spatial dimensions (height and width) of the input feature maps while retaining the most important information.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] There are several non-linear functions to implement pooling, where *max pooling* and *average pooling* are the most common.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Pooling aggregates information from small regions of the input creating partitions of the input feature map, typically using a fixed-size window (like 2x2) and applying a stride (often 2) to move the window across the input.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Note that without using a stride greater than 1, pooling would not perform downsampling, as it would simply move the pooling window across the input one step at a time, without reducing the size of the feature map.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In other words, the stride is what actually causes the downsampling by determining how much the pooling window moves over the input.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Intuitively, the exact location of a feature is less important than its rough location relative to other features.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is the idea behind the use of pooling in convolutional neural networks.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The pooling layer serves to progressively reduce the spatial size of the representation, to reduce the number of parameters, memory footprint and amount of computation in the network, and hence to also control overfitting.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is common to periodically insert a pooling layer between successive convolutional layers (each one typically followed by an activation function, such as a ReLU layer) in a CNN architecture.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] While pooling layers contribute to local translation invariance, they do not provide global translation invariance in a CNN, unless a form of global pooling is used.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The pooling layer commonly operates independently on every depth, or slice, of the input and resizes it spatially.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The depth dimension remains unchanged (this is true for other forms of pooling as well).
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In addition to max pooling, pooling units can use other functions, such as average pooling or ℓ2-norm pooling.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Average pooling was often used historically but has recently fallen out of favor compared to max pooling, which generally performs better in practice.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Due to the effects of fast spatial reduction of the size of the representation, there is a recent trend towards using smaller filters or discarding pooling layers altogether.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A channel max pooling (CMP) operation layer conducts the MP operation along the channel side among the corresponding positions of the consecutive feature maps for the purpose of redundant information elimination.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The CMP makes the significant features gather together within fewer channels, which is important for fine-grained image classification that needs more discriminating features.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Meanwhile, another advantage of the CMP operation is to make the channel number of feature maps smaller before it connects to the first fully connected (FC) layer.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Similar to the MP operation, we denote the input feature maps and output feature maps of a CMP layer as F ∈ R(C×M×N) and C ∈ R(c×M×N), respectively, where C and c are the channel numbers of the input and output feature maps, M and N are the widths and the height of the feature maps, respectively.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Note that the CMP operation only changes the channel number of the feature maps.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The width and the height of the feature maps are not changed, which is different from the MP operation.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] ReLU is the abbreviation of rectified linear unit.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It was proposed by Alston Householder in 1941, and used in CNN by Kunihiko Fukushima in 1969.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] ReLU applies the non-saturating activation function ${\textstyle f(x)=\max(0,x)}$ .
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It effectively removes negative values from an activation map by setting them to zero.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It introduces nonlinearity to the decision function and in the overall network without affecting the receptive fields of the convolution layers.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2011, Xavier Glorot, Antoine Bordes and Yoshua Bengio found that ReLU enables better training of deeper networks, compared to widely used activation functions prior to 2011.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Other functions can also be used to increase nonlinearity, for example the saturating hyperbolic tangent $f(x)=\tanh(x)$ , $f(x)=|\tanh(x)|$ , and the sigmoid function ${\textstyle \sigma (x)=(1+e^{-x})^{-1}}$ .
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] ReLU is often preferred to other functions because it trains the neural network several times faster without a significant penalty to generalization accuracy.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] After several convolutional and max pooling layers, the final classification is done via fully connected layers.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Neurons in a fully connected layer have connections to all activations in the previous layer, as seen in regular (non-convolutional) artificial neural networks.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their activations can thus be computed as an affine transformation, with matrix multiplication followed by a bias offset (vector addition of a learned or fixed bias term).
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The "loss layer", or "loss function", exemplifies how training penalizes the deviation between the predicted output of the network, and the true data labels (during supervised learning).
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Various loss functions can be used, depending on the specific task.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The Softmax loss function is used for predicting a single class of *K* mutually exclusive classes.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Sigmoid cross-entropy loss is used for predicting *K* independent probability values in $[0,1]$ .
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Euclidean loss is used for regressing to real-valued labels $(-\infty ,\infty )$ .
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Hyperparameters are various settings that are used to control the learning process.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs use more hyperparameters than a standard multilayer perceptron (MLP).
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Padding is the addition of (typically) 0-valued pixels on the borders of an image.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is done so that the border pixels are not undervalued (lost) from the output because they would ordinarily participate in only a single receptive field instance.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The padding applied is typically one less than the corresponding kernel dimension.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, a convolutional layer using 3x3 kernels would receive a 2-pixel pad, that is 1 pixel on each side of the image.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The stride is the number of pixels that the analysis window moves on each iteration.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A stride of 2 means that each kernel is offset by 2 pixels from its predecessor.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Since feature map size decreases with depth, layers near the input layer tend to have fewer filters while higher layers can have more.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] To equalize computation at each layer, the product of feature values *va* with pixel position is kept roughly constant across layers.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Preserving more information about the input would require keeping the total number of activations (number of feature maps times number of pixel positions) non-decreasing from one layer to the next.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The number of feature maps directly controls the capacity and depends on the number of available examples and task complexity.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Common filter sizes found in the literature vary greatly, and are usually chosen based on the data set.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Typical filter sizes range from 1x1 to 7x7.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] As two famous examples, AlexNet used 3x3, 5x5, and 11x11.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The challenge is to find the right level of granularity so as to create abstractions at the proper scale, given a particular data set, and without overfitting.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Max pooling is typically used, often with a 2x2 dimension.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This implies that the input is drastically downsampled, reducing processing cost.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Greater pooling reduces the dimension of the signal, and may result in unacceptable information loss.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Often, non-overlapping pooling windows perform best.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Dilation involves ignoring pixels within a kernel.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This reduces processing memory potentially without significant signal loss.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A dilation of 2 on a 3x3 kernel expands the kernel to 5x5, while still processing 9 (evenly spaced) pixels.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Accordingly, dilation of 4 expands the kernel to 7x7.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is commonly assumed that CNNs are invariant to shifts of the input.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolution or pooling layers within a CNN that do not have a stride greater than one are indeed equivariant to translations of the input.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Furthermore, if a CNN makes use of fully connected layers, translation equivariance does not imply translation invariance, as the fully connected layers are not invariant to shifts of the input.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One solution for complete translation invariance is avoiding any down-sampling throughout the network and applying global average pooling at the last layer.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Additionally, several other partial solutions have been proposed, such as anti-aliasing before downsampling operations, spatial transformer networks, data augmentation, subsampling combined with pooling, and capsule neural networks.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The accuracy of the final model is typically estimated on a sub-part of the dataset set apart at the start, often called a test set.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Alternatively, methods such as *k*-fold cross-validation are applied.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Other strategies include using conformal prediction.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Regularization is a process of introducing additional information to solve an ill-posed problem or to prevent overfitting.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs use various types of regularization.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Because networks have so many parameters, they are prone to overfitting.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One method to reduce overfitting is dropout, introduced in 2014.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] At each training stage, individual nodes are either "dropped out" of the net (ignored) with probability $1-p$ or kept with probability p , so that a reduced network is left; incoming and outgoing edges to a dropped-out node are also removed.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Only the reduced network is trained on the data in that stage.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The removed nodes are then reinserted into the network with their original weights.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the training stages, p is usually 0.5; for input nodes, it is typically much higher because information is directly lost when input nodes are ignored.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] At testing time after training has finished, we would ideally like to find a sample average of all possible $2^{n}$ dropped-out networks; unfortunately this is unfeasible for large values of n .
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, we can find an approximation by using the full network with each node's output weighted by a factor of p , so the expected value of the output of any node is the same as in the training stages.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is the biggest contribution of the dropout method: although it effectively generates $2^{n}$ neural nets, and as such allows for model combination, at test time only a single network needs to be tested.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] By avoiding training all nodes on all training data, dropout decreases overfitting.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The method also significantly improves training speed.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This makes the model combination practical, even for deep neural networks.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The technique seems to reduce node interactions, leading them to learn more robust features that better generalize to new data.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] DropConnect is the generalization of dropout in which each connection, rather than each output unit, can be dropped with probability $1-p$ .
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each unit thus receives input from a random subset of units in the previous layer.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] DropConnect is similar to dropout as it introduces dynamic sparsity within the model, but differs in that the sparsity is on the weights, rather than the output vectors of a layer.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In other words, the fully connected layer with DropConnect becomes a sparsely connected layer in which the connections are chosen at random during the training stage.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A major drawback to dropout is that it does not have the same benefits for convolutional layers, where the neurons are not fully connected.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This approach is free of hyperparameters and can be combined with other regularization approaches, such as dropout and data augmentation.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] An alternate view of stochastic pooling is that it is equivalent to standard max pooling but with many copies of an input image, each having small local deformations.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is similar to explicit elastic deformations of the input images, which delivers excellent performance on the MNIST data set.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Using stochastic pooling in a multilayer model gives an exponential number of deformations since the selections in higher layers are independent of those below.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Because the degree of model overfitting is determined by both its power and the amount of training it receives, providing a convolutional network with more training examples can reduce overfitting.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Because there is often not enough available data to train, especially considering that some part should be spared for later testing, two approaches are to either generate new data from scratch (if possible) or perturb existing data to create new ones.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, input images can be cropped, rotated, or rescaled to create new examples with the same labels as the original training set.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One of the simplest methods to prevent overfitting of a network is to simply stop the training before overfitting has had a chance to occur.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It comes with the disadvantage that the learning process is halted.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Another simple way to prevent overfitting is to limit the number of parameters, typically by limiting the number of hidden units in each layer or limiting network depth.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For convolutional networks, the filter size also affects the number of parameters.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Limiting the number of parameters restricts the predictive power of the network directly, reducing the complexity of the function that it can perform on the data, and thus limits the amount of overfitting.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A simple form of added regularizer is weight decay, which simply adds an additional error, proportional to the sum of weights (L1 norm) or squared magnitude (L2 norm) of the weight vector, to the error at each node.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The level of acceptable model complexity can be reduced by increasing the proportionality constant('alpha' hyperparameter), thus increasing the penalty for large weight vectors.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] L2 regularization is the most common form of regularization.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It can be implemented by penalizing the squared magnitude of all parameters directly in the objective.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The L2 regularization has the intuitive interpretation of heavily penalizing peaky weight vectors and preferring diffuse weight vectors.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Due to multiplicative interactions between weights and inputs this has the useful property of encouraging the network to use all of its inputs a little rather than some of its inputs a lot.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It makes the weight vectors sparse during optimization.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In other words, neurons with L1 regularization end up using only a sparse subset of their most important inputs and become nearly invariant to the noisy inputs.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] L1 with L2 regularization can be combined; this is called elastic net regularization.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Another form of regularization is to enforce an absolute upper bound on the magnitude of the weight vector for every neuron and use projected gradient descent to enforce the constraint.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In practice, this corresponds to performing the parameter update as normal, and then enforcing the constraint by clamping the weight vector ${\vec {w}}$ of every neuron to satisfy $\|{\vec {w}}\|_{2}<c$ .
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Some papers report improvements when using this form of regularization.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Pooling loses the precise spatial relationships between high-level parts (such as nose and mouth in a face image).
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] These relationships are needed for identity recognition.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Overlapping the pools so that each feature occurs in multiple pools, helps retain the information.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Translation alone cannot extrapolate the understanding of geometric relationships to a radically new viewpoint, such as a different orientation or scale.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] On the other hand, people are very good at extrapolating; after seeing a new shape once they can recognize it from a different viewpoint.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] An earlier common way to deal with this problem is to train the network on transformed data in different orientations, scales, lighting, etc. so that the network can cope with these variations.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This is computationally intensive for large data-sets.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The alternative is to use a hierarchy of coordinate frames and use a group of neurons to represent a conjunction of the shape of the feature and its pose relative to the retina.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The pose relative to the retina is the relationship between the coordinate frame of the retina and the intrinsic features' coordinate frame.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Thus, one way to represent something is to embed the coordinate frame within it.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This allows large features to be recognized by using the consistency of the poses of their parts (e.g. nose and mouth poses make a consistent prediction of the pose of the whole face).
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This approach ensures that the higher-level entity (e.g. face) is present when the lower-level (e.g. nose and mouth) agree on its prediction of the pose.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The vectors of neuronal activity that represent pose ("pose vectors") allow spatial transformations modeled as linear operations that make it easier for the network to learn the hierarchy of visual entities and generalize across viewpoints.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This is similar to the way the human visual system imposes coordinate frames in order to represent shapes.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs are often used in image recognition systems.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In 2012, an error rate of 0.23% on the MNIST database was reported.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Another paper on using CNN for image classification reported that the learning process was "surprisingly fast"; in the same paper, the best published results as of 2011 were achieved in the MNIST database and the NORB database.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Subsequently, a similar CNN called AlexNet won the ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge 2012.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] When applied to facial recognition, CNNs achieved a large decrease in error rate.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Another paper reported a 97.6% recognition rate on "5,600 still images of more than 10 subjects".
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs were used to assess video quality in an objective way after manual training; the resulting system had a very low root mean square error.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge is a benchmark in object classification and detection, with millions of images and hundreds of object classes.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In the ILSVRC 2014, a large-scale visual recognition challenge, almost every highly ranked team used CNN as their basic framework.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The winner GoogLeNet (the foundation of DeepDream) increased the mean average precision of object detection to 0.439329, and reduced classification error to 0.06656, the best result to date.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Its network applied more than 30 layers.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] That performance of convolutional neural networks on the ImageNet tests was close to that of humans.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The best algorithms still struggle with objects that are small or thin, such as a small ant on a stem of a flower or a person holding a quill in their hand.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] They also have trouble with images that have been distorted with filters, an increasingly common phenomenon with modern digital cameras.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] For example, they are not good at classifying objects into fine-grained categories such as the particular breed of dog or species of bird, whereas convolutional neural networks handle this.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In 2015, a many-layered CNN demonstrated the ability to spot faces from a wide range of angles, including upside down, even when partially occluded, with competitive performance.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The network was trained on a database of 200,000 images that included faces at various angles and orientations and a further 20 million images without faces.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] They used batches of 128 images over 50,000 iterations.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Compared to image data domains, there is relatively little work on applying CNNs to video classification.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Video is more complex than images since it has another (temporal) dimension.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] However, some extensions of CNNs into the video domain have been explored.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] One approach is to treat space and time as equivalent dimensions of the input and perform convolutions in both time and space.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Another way is to fuse the features of two convolutional neural networks, one for the spatial and one for the temporal stream.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Long short-term memory (LSTM) recurrent units are typically incorporated after the CNN to account for inter-frame or inter-clip dependencies.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Unsupervised learning schemes for training spatio-temporal features have been introduced, based on convolutional gated restricted Boltzmann machines and independent subspace analysis.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Its application can be seen in text-to-video models.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs have also been explored for natural language processing.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNN models are effective for various NLP problems and achieved excellent results in semantic parsing, search query retrieval, sentence modeling, classification, prediction and other traditional NLP tasks.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Compared to traditional language processing methods such as recurrent neural networks, CNNs can represent different contextual realities of language that do not rely on a series-sequence assumption, while RNNs are better suitable when classical time series modeling is required.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs have been applied in ecological and behavioral research to automatically detect and quantify animal behavior from visual data, enabling identification of animals, tracking of individuals, estimation of pose, and classification of specific actions such as feeding, and social interactions.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Combined with multi-object tracking and temporal modeling, these systems can extract behavioral sequences over extended recordings, reducing reliance on manual annotation and increasing throughput for studies of individual variation, social networks, and collective dynamics.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A CNN with 1-D convolutions was used on time series in the frequency domain (spectral residual) by an unsupervised model to detect anomalies in the time domain.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Predicting the interaction between molecules and biological proteins can identify potential treatments.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In 2015, Atomwise introduced AtomNet, the first deep learning neural network for structure-based drug design.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The system trains directly on 3-dimensional representations of chemical interactions.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Similar to how image recognition networks learn to compose smaller, spatially proximate features into larger, complex structures, AtomNet discovers chemical features, such as aromaticity, sp3 carbons, and hydrogen bonding.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Subsequently, AtomNet was used to predict novel candidate biomolecules for multiple disease targets, most notably treatments for the Ebola virus and multiple sclerosis.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs have been used in the game of checkers.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] From 1999 to 2001, Fogel and Chellapilla published papers showing how a convolutional neural network could learn to play checkers using co-evolution.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The learning process did not use prior human professional games, but rather focused on a minimal set of information contained in the checkerboard: the location and type of pieces, and the difference in number of pieces between the two sides.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Ultimately, the program (Blondie24) was tested on 165 games against players and ranked in the highest 0.4%.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] It also earned a win against the program Chinook at its "expert" level of play.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In December 2014, Clark and Storkey published a paper showing that a CNN trained by supervised learning from a database of human professional games could outperform GNU Go and win some games against Monte Carlo tree search Fuego 1.1 in a fraction of the time it took Fuego to play.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Later it was announced that a large 12-layer convolutional neural network had correctly predicted the professional move in 55% of positions, equalling the accuracy of a 6 dan human player.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A couple of CNNs for choosing moves to try ("policy network") and evaluating positions ("value network") driving MCTS were used by AlphaGo, the first to beat the best human player at the time.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Recurrent neural networks are generally considered the best neural network architectures for time series forecasting (and sequence modeling in general), but recent studies show that convolutional networks can perform comparably or even better.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Dilated convolutions might enable one-dimensional convolutional neural networks to effectively learn time series dependences.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutions can be implemented more efficiently than RNN-based solutions, and they do not suffer from vanishing (or exploding) gradients.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutional networks can provide an improved forecasting performance when there are multiple similar time series to learn from.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs can also be applied to further tasks in time series analysis (e.g., time series classification or quantile forecasting).
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] As archaeological findings such as clay tablets with cuneiform writing are increasingly acquired using 3D scanners, benchmark datasets are becoming available, including *HeiCuBeDa* providing almost 2000 normalized 2-D and 3-D datasets prepared with the GigaMesh Software Framework.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] So curvature-based measures are used in conjunction with geometric neural networks (GNNs), e.g. for period classification of those clay tablets being among the oldest documents of human history.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] For many applications, training data is not very available.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutional neural networks usually require a large amount of training data in order to avoid overfitting.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A common technique is to train the network on a larger data set from a related domain.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Once the network parameters have converged an additional training step is performed using the in-domain data to fine-tune the network weights, this is known as transfer learning.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Furthermore, this technique allows convolutional network architectures to successfully be applied to problems with tiny training sets.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] End-to-end training and prediction are common practice in computer vision.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] However, human interpretable explanations are required for critical systems such as self-driving cars.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] With recent advances in visual salience, spatial attention, and temporal attention, the most critical spatial regions/temporal instants could be visualized to justify the CNN predictions.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A deep Q-network (DQN) is a type of deep learning model that combines a deep neural network with Q-learning, a form of reinforcement learning.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Unlike earlier reinforcement learning agents, DQNs that utilize CNNs can learn directly from high-dimensional sensory inputs via reinforcement learning.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Preliminary results were presented in 2014, with an accompanying paper in February 2015.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The research described an application to Atari 2600 gaming.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Other deep reinforcement learning models preceded it.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutional deep belief networks (CDBN) have structure very similar to convolutional neural networks and are trained similarly to deep belief networks.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Therefore, they exploit the 2D structure of images, like CNNs do, and make use of pre-training like deep belief networks.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] They provide a generic structure that can be used in many image and signal processing tasks.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Benchmark results on standard image datasets like CIFAR have been obtained using CDBNs.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The feed-forward architecture of convolutional neural networks was extended in the neural abstraction pyramid by lateral and feedback connections.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The resulting recurrent convolutional network allows for the flexible incorporation of contextual information to iteratively resolve local ambiguities.
[src:optical-character-recognition/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In contrast to previous models, image-like outputs at the highest resolution were generated, e.g., for semantic segmentation, image reconstruction, and object localization tasks.
[src:optical-character-recognition/feature-extraction] Beyond machine learning, the principles of feature engineering are applied in various scientific fields, including physics.
[src:optical-character-recognition/feature-extraction] For example, physicists construct dimensionless numbers such as the Reynolds number in fluid dynamics, the Nusselt number in heat transfer, and the Archimedes number in sedimentation.
[src:optical-character-recognition/feature-extraction] They also develop first approximations of solutions, such as analytical solutions for the strength of materials in mechanics.
[src:optical-character-recognition/feature-extraction] One of the applications of feature engineering has been clustering of feature-objects or sample-objects in a dataset.
[src:optical-character-recognition/feature-extraction] Especially, feature engineering based on matrix decomposition has been extensively used for data clustering under non-negativity constraints on the feature coefficients.
[src:optical-character-recognition/feature-extraction] These include *Non-Negative Matrix Factorization* (NMF), *Non-Negative Matrix-Tri Factorization* (NMTF), *Non-Negative Tensor Decomposition/Factorization* (NTF/NTD), etc.
[src:optical-character-recognition/feature-extraction] The non-negativity constraints on coefficients of the feature vectors mined by the above-stated algorithms yields a part-based representation, and different factor matrices exhibit natural clustering properties.
[src:optical-character-recognition/feature-extraction] Several extensions of the above-stated feature engineering methods have been reported in literature, including *orthogonality-constrained factorization* for hard clustering, and *manifold learning* to overcome inherent issues with these algorithms.
[src:optical-character-recognition/feature-extraction] Other classes of feature engineering algorithms include leveraging a common hidden structure across multiple inter-related datasets to obtain a consensus (common) clustering scheme.
[src:optical-character-recognition/feature-extraction] An example is *Multi-view Classification based on Consensus Matrix Decomposition* (MCMD), which mines a common clustering scheme across multiple datasets.
[src:optical-character-recognition/feature-extraction] Coupled matrix and tensor decompositions are popular in multi-view feature engineering.
[src:optical-character-recognition/feature-extraction] Feature engineering in machine learning and statistical modeling involves selecting, creating, transforming, and extracting data features.
[src:optical-character-recognition/feature-extraction] Even relatively insignificant features may contribute to a model.
[src:optical-character-recognition/feature-extraction] Feature selection can reduce the number of features to prevent a model from becoming too specific to the training data set (overfitting).
[src:optical-character-recognition/feature-extraction] Feature explosion occurs when the number of identified features is too large for effective model estimation or optimization.
[src:optical-character-recognition/feature-extraction] Feature explosion can be limited via techniques such as regularization, kernel methods, and feature selection.
[src:optical-character-recognition/feature-extraction] Automation of feature engineering is a research topic that dates back to the 1990s.
[src:optical-character-recognition/feature-extraction] Machine learning software that incorporates automated feature engineering has been commercially available since 2016.
[src:optical-character-recognition/feature-extraction] Multi-relational Decision Tree Learning (MRDTL) extends traditional decision tree methods to relational databases, handling complex data relationships across tables.
[src:optical-character-recognition/feature-extraction] It innovatively uses selection graphs as decision nodes, refined systematically until a specific termination criterion is reached.
[src:optical-character-recognition/feature-extraction] Most MRDTL studies base implementations on relational databases, which results in many redundant operations.
[src:optical-character-recognition/feature-extraction] These redundancies can be reduced by using techniques such as tuple id propagation.
[src:optical-character-recognition/feature-extraction] The deep feature synthesis (DFS) algorithm beat 615 of 906 human teams in a competition.
[src:optical-character-recognition/feature-extraction] The feature store is where the features are stored and organized for the explicit purpose of being used to either train models (by data scientists) or make predictions (by applications that have a trained model).
[src:optical-character-recognition/feature-extraction] A feature store includes the ability to store code used to generate features, apply the code to raw data, and serve those features to models upon request.
[src:optical-character-recognition/feature-extraction] Useful capabilities include feature versioning and policies governing the circumstances under which features can be used.
[src:optical-character-recognition/feature-extraction] Feature stores can be standalone software tools or built into machine learning platforms.
[src:optical-character-recognition/feature-extraction] Feature engineering can be a time-consuming and error-prone process, as it requires domain expertise and often involves trial and error.
[src:optical-character-recognition/feature-extraction] Deep learning algorithms may be used to process a large raw dataset without having to resort to feature engineering.
[src:optical-character-recognition/feature-extraction] However, deep learning algorithms still require careful preprocessing and cleaning of the input data.
[src:optical-character-recognition/feature-extraction] In addition, choosing the right architecture, hyperparameters, and optimization algorithm for a deep neural network can be a challenging and iterative process.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] In digital image processing and computer vision, **image segmentation** is the process of partitioning a digital image into multiple **image segments**, also known as **image regions** or **image objects** (sets of pixels).
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The goal of segmentation is to simplify and/or change the representation of an image into something that is more meaningful and easier to analyze.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Image segmentation is typically used to locate objects and boundaries (lines, curves, etc.) in images.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] More precisely, image segmentation is the process of assigning a label to every pixel in an image such that pixels with the same label share certain characteristics.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The result of image segmentation is a set of segments that collectively cover the entire image, or a set of contours extracted from the image (see edge detection).
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Each of the pixels in a region are similar with respect to some characteristic or computed property, such as color, intensity, or texture.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Adjacent regions are significantly different with respect to the same characteristic(s).
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] When applied to a stack of images, typical in medical imaging, the resulting contours after image segmentation can be used to create 3D reconstructions with the help of geometry reconstruction algorithms like marching cubes.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Several general-purpose algorithms and techniques have been developed for image segmentation.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] To be useful, these techniques must typically be combined with a domain's specific knowledge in order to effectively solve the domain's segmentation problems.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] There are two classes of segmentation techniques.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The simplest method of image segmentation is called the thresholding method.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] This method is based on a clip-level (or a threshold value) to turn a gray-scale image into a binary image.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The key of this method is to select the threshold value (or values when multiple-levels are selected).
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Several popular methods are used in industry including the maximum entropy method, balanced histogram thresholding, Otsu's method (maximum variance), and k-means clustering.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Recently, methods have been developed for thresholding computed tomography (CT) images.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The key idea is that, unlike Otsu's method, the thresholds are derived from the radiographs instead of the (reconstructed) image.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] New methods suggest the use of multi-dimensional, fuzzy rule-based, non-linear thresholds.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] In these approaches, the decision regarding each pixel's membership in a segment is based on multi-dimensional rules derived from fuzzy logic and evolutionary algorithms, considering factors such as image lighting, environment, and application.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Note that a common technique to improve performance for large images is to downsample the image, compute the clusters, and then reassign the values to the larger image if necessary.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The K-means algorithm is an iterative technique that is used to partition an image into *K* clusters.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] In this case, distance is the squared or absolute difference between a pixel and a cluster center.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The difference is typically based on pixel color, intensity, texture, and location, or a weighted combination of these factors.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] *K* can be selected manually, randomly, or by a heuristic.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] This algorithm is guaranteed to converge, but it may not return the optimal solution.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The quality of the solution depends on the initial set of clusters and the value of *K*.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The Mean Shift algorithm is a technique that is used to partition an image into an unknown apriori number of clusters.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] This has the advantage of not having to start with an initial guess of such parameter which makes it a better general solution for more diverse cases.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Motion based segmentation is a technique that relies on motion in the image to perform segmentation.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The idea is simple: look at the differences between a pair of images.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Assuming the object of interest is moving, the difference will be exactly that object.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Improving on this idea, Kenney et al. proposed interactive segmentation [2].
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] They use a robot to poke objects in order to generate the motion signal necessary for motion-based segmentation.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Interactive segmentation follows the interactive perception framework proposed by Dov Katz [3] and Oliver Brock [4].
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Another technique that is based on motion is rigid motion segmentation.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Compression based methods postulate that the optimal segmentation is the one that minimizes, over all possible segmentations, the coding length of the data.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The connection between these two concepts is that segmentation tries to find patterns in an image and any regularity in the image can be used to compress it.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The method describes each segment by its texture and boundary shape.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Texture is encoded by lossy compression in a way similar to minimum description length (MDL) principle, but here the length of the data given the model is approximated by the number of samples times the entropy of the model.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The texture in each region is modeled by a multivariate normal distribution whose entropy has a closed form expression.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] An interesting property of this model is that the estimated entropy bounds the true entropy of the data from above.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] This is because among all distributions with a given mean and covariance, normal distribution has the largest entropy.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Thus, the true coding length cannot be more than what the algorithm tries to minimize.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] For any given segmentation of an image, this scheme yields the number of bits required to encode that image based on the given segmentation.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Thus, among all possible segmentations of an image, the goal is to find the segmentation which produces the shortest coding length.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] This can be achieved by a simple agglomerative clustering method.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The distortion in the lossy compression determines the coarseness of the segmentation and its optimal value may differ for each image.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] This parameter can be estimated heuristically from the contrast of textures in an image.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] For example, when the textures in an image are similar, such as in camouflage images, stronger sensitivity and thus lower quantization is required.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Histogram-based methods are very efficient compared to other image segmentation methods because they typically require only one pass through the pixels.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] In this technique, a histogram is computed from all of the pixels in the image, and the peaks and valleys in the histogram are used to locate the clusters in the image.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Color or intensity can be used as the measure.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] A refinement of this technique is to recursively apply the histogram-seeking method to clusters in the image in order to divide them into smaller clusters.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] This operation is repeated with smaller and smaller clusters until no more clusters are formed.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] One disadvantage of the histogram-seeking method is that it may be difficult to identify significant peaks and valleys in the image.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Histogram-based approaches can also be quickly adapted to apply to multiple frames, while maintaining their single pass efficiency.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The histogram can be done in multiple fashions when multiple frames are considered.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The same approach that is taken with one frame can be applied to multiple, and after the results are merged, peaks and valleys that were previously difficult to identify are more likely to be distinguishable.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The histogram can also be applied on a per-pixel basis where the resulting information is used to determine the most frequent color for the pixel location.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] This approach segments based on active objects and a static environment, resulting in a different type of segmentation useful in video tracking.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Edge detection is a well-developed field on its own within image processing.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Region boundaries and edges are closely related, since there is often a sharp adjustment in intensity at the region boundaries.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Edge detection techniques have therefore been used as the base of another segmentation technique.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The edges identified by edge detection are often disconnected.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] To segment an object from an image however, one needs closed region boundaries.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The desired edges are the boundaries between such objects or spatial-taxons.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Spatial-taxons are information granules, consisting of a crisp pixel region, stationed at abstraction levels within a hierarchical nested scene architecture.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] They are similar to the Gestalt psychological designation of figure-ground, but are extended to include foreground, object groups, objects and salient object parts.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Edge detection methods can be applied to the spatial-taxon region, in the same manner they would be applied to a silhouette.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Segmentation methods can also be applied to edges obtained from edge detectors.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The detection of isolated points in an image is a fundamental part of image segmentation.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] This process primarily depends on the second derivative, indicating the use of the Laplacian operator.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The Laplacian operator is employed such that the partial derivatives are derived from a specific equation.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] This mathematical expression can be implemented by convolving with an appropriate mask.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] If we extend this equation to three dimensions (x,y,z), the intensity at each pixel location around a central pixel at (x, y, z) is replaced by their corresponding values.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] This equation becomes particularly useful when we assume that all pixels have unit spacing along each axis.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] A sphere mask has been developed for use with three-dimensional datasets.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The sphere mask is designed to use only integer arithmetic during calculations, thereby eliminating the need for floating-point hardware or software.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] When applying these concepts to actual images represented as arrays of numbers, we need to consider what happens when we reach an edge or border region.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] This above equation is used to determine whether a point in the image is an isolated point based on the response magnitude $|R(x,y)|$ and a threshold value T .
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] If the response magnitude is greater than or equal to the threshold, the function returns 1, indicating the presence of an isolated point; otherwise, it returns 0.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] This helps in the effective detection and segmentation of isolated points in the image.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The detection of isolated points has significant applications in various fields, including X-ray image processing.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] For instance, an original X-ray image of a turbine blade can be examined pixel-by-pixel to detect porosity in the upper-right quadrant of the blade.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The result of applying an edge detector's response to this X-ray image can be approximated.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] This demonstrates the segmentation of isolated points in an image with the aid of single-pixel probes.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] This method is a combination of three characteristics of the image: partition of the image based on histogram analysis is checked by high compactness of the clusters (objects), and high gradients of their borders.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] For that purpose two spaces have to be introduced: one space is the one-dimensional histogram of brightness *H* = *H*(*B*); the second space is the dual 3-dimensional space of the original image itself *B* = *B*(*x*, *y*).
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The first space allows to measure how compactly the brightness of the image is distributed by calculating a minimal clustering kmin.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The bitmap *b* is an object in dual space.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] On that bitmap a measure has to be defined reflecting how compact distributed black (or white) pixels are.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] So, the goal is to find objects with good borders.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] For all *T* the measure *M*DC = *G*/(*k* × *L*) has to be calculated (where *k* is difference in brightness between the object and the background, *L* is length of all borders, and *G* is mean gradient on the borders).
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Maximum of MDC defines the segmentation.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Region-growing methods rely mainly on the assumption that the neighboring pixels within one region have similar values.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The common procedure is to compare one pixel with its neighbors.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] If a similarity criterion is satisfied, the pixel can be set to belong to the same cluster as one or more of its neighbors.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The selection of the similarity criterion is significant and the results are influenced by noise in all instances.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The method of Statistical Region Merging (SRM) starts by building the graph of pixels using 4-connectedness with edges weighted by the absolute value of the intensity difference.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Initially each pixel forms a single pixel region.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] SRM then sorts those edges in a priority queue and decides whether or not to merge the current regions belonging to the edge pixels using a statistical predicate.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] One region-growing method is the seeded region growing method.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] This method takes a set of seeds as input along with the image.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The seeds mark each of the objects to be segmented.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The regions are iteratively grown by comparison of all unallocated neighboring pixels to the regions.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The difference between a pixel's intensity value and the region's mean, $\delta$ , is used as a measure of similarity.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The pixel with the smallest difference measured in this way is assigned to the respective region.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] This process continues until all pixels are assigned to a region.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Because seeded region growing requires seeds as additional input, the segmentation results are dependent on the choice of seeds, and noise in the image can cause the seeds to be poorly placed.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Another region-growing method is the unseeded region growing method.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] It is a modified algorithm that does not require explicit seeds.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] It starts with a single region $A_{1}$ —the pixel chosen here does not markedly influence the final segmentation.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] At each iteration it considers the neighboring pixels in the same way as seeded region growing.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] It differs from seeded region growing in that if the minimum $\delta$ is less than a predefined threshold T then it is added to the respective region $A_{j}$ .
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] If not, then the pixel is considered different from all current regions $A_{i}$ and a new region $A_{n+1}$ is created with this pixel.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] One variant of this technique, proposed by Haralick and Shapiro (1985), is based on pixel intensities.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The mean and scatter of the region and the intensity of the candidate pixel are used to compute a test statistic.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] If the test statistic is sufficiently small, the pixel is added to the region, and the region's mean and scatter are recomputed.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Otherwise, the pixel is rejected, and is used to form a new region.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] A special region-growing method is called $\lambda$ -connected segmentation (see also lambda-connectedness).
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] It is based on pixel intensities and neighborhood-linking paths.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] A degree of connectivity (connectedness) is calculated based on a path that is formed by pixels.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] For a certain value of $\lambda$ , two pixels are called $\lambda$ -connected if there is a path linking those two pixels and the connectedness of this path is at least $\lambda$ . $\lambda$ -connectedness is an equivalence relation.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Split-and-merge segmentation is based on a quadtree partition of an image.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] It is sometimes called quadtree segmentation.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] This method starts at the root of the tree that represents the whole image.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] If it is found non-uniform (not homogeneous), then it is split into four child squares (the splitting process), and so on.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] If, in contrast, four child squares are homogeneous, they are merged as several connected components (the merging process).
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The node in the tree is a segmented node.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] This process continues recursively until no further splits or merges are possible.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] When a special data structure is involved in the implementation of the algorithm of the method, its time complexity can reach $O(n\log n)$ , an optimal algorithm of the method.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Using a partial differential equation (PDE)-based method and solving the PDE equation by a numerical scheme, one can segment the image.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Curve propagation is a popular technique in this category, with numerous applications to object extraction, object tracking, stereo reconstruction, etc.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The central idea is to evolve an initial curve towards the lowest potential of a cost function, where its definition reflects the task to be addressed.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] As for most inverse problems, the minimization of the cost functional is non-trivial and imposes certain smoothness constraints on the solution, which in the present case can be expressed as geometrical constraints on the evolving curve.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Lagrangian techniques are based on parameterizing the contour according to some sampling strategy and then evolving each element according to image and internal terms.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Nowadays, efficient "discretized" formulations have been developed to address these limitations while maintaining high efficiency.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] In both cases, energy minimization is generally conducted using a steepest-gradient descent, whereby derivatives are computed using, e.g., finite differences.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The level-set method was initially proposed to track moving interfaces by Dervieux and Thomasset in 1979 and 1981 and was later reinvented by Osher and Sethian in 1988.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] This has spread across various imaging domains in the late 1990s.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] It can be used to efficiently address the problem of curve/surface/etc. propagation in an implicit manner.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The central idea is to represent the evolving contour using a signed function whose zero corresponds to the actual contour.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Then, according to the motion equation of the contour, one can easily derive a similar flow for the implicit surface that when applied to the zero level will reflect the propagation of the contour.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The level-set method affords numerous advantages: it is implicit, is parameter-free, provides a direct way to estimate the geometric properties of the evolving structure, allows for change of topology, and is intrinsic.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] It can be used to define an optimization framework, as proposed by Zhao, Merriman and Osher in 1996.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] One can conclude that it is a very convenient framework for addressing numerous applications of computer vision and medical image analysis.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Research into various level-set data structures has led to very efficient implementations of this method.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The fast marching method has been used in image segmentation, and this model has been improved (permitting both positive and negative propagation speeds) in an approach called the generalized fast marching method.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The goal of variational methods is to find a segmentation which is optimal with respect to a specific energy functional.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The functionals consist of a data fitting term and a regularizing terms.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] A minimizer $u^{*}$ is a piecewise constant image which has an optimal tradeoff between the squared L2 distance to the given image f and the total length of its jump set.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The jump set of $u^{*}$ defines a segmentation.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The relative weight of the energies is tuned by the parameter $\gamma >0$ .
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The binary variant of the Potts model, i.e., if the range of u is restricted to two values, is often called Chan-Vese model.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The functional value is the sum of the total length of the segmentation curve K , the smoothness of the approximation u , and its distance to the original image f .
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The weight of the smoothness penalty is adjusted by $\mu >0$ .
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The Potts model is often called piecewise constant Mumford-Shah model as it can be seen as the degenerate case $\mu \to \infty$ .
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The optimization problems are known to be NP-hard in general but near-minimizing strategies work well in practice.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Classical algorithms are graduated non-convexity and Ambrosio-Tortorelli approximation.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Graph partitioning methods are an effective tools for image segmentation since they model the impact of pixel neighborhoods on a given cluster of pixels or pixel, under the assumption of homogeneity in images.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] In these methods, the image is modeled as a weighted, undirected graph.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Usually a pixel or a group of pixels are associated with nodes and edge weights define the (dis)similarity between the neighborhood pixels.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The graph (image) is then partitioned according to a criterion designed to model "good" clusters.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Each partition of the nodes (pixels) output from these algorithms are considered an object segment in the image; see Segmentation-based object categorization.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Some popular algorithms of this category are normalized cuts, random walker, minimum cut, isoperimetric partitioning, minimum spanning tree-based segmentation, and segmentation-based object categorization.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The application of Markov random fields (MRF) for images was suggested in early 1984 by Geman and Geman.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Their strong mathematical foundation and ability to provide a global optimum even when defined on local features proved to be the foundation for novel research in the domain of image analysis, de-noising and segmentation.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] MRFs are completely characterized by their prior probability distributions, marginal probability distributions, cliques, smoothing constraint as well as criterion for updating values.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The criterion for image segmentation using MRFs is restated as finding the labelling scheme which has maximum probability for a given set of features.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The broad categories of image segmentation using MRFs are supervised and unsupervised segmentation.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] In terms of image segmentation, the function that MRFs seek to maximize is the probability of identifying a labelling scheme given a particular set of features are detected in the image.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] This is a restatement of the maximum a posteriori estimation method.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] 3. where *fi* ∈ Σ is the set containing features extracted for pixel i and define an initial set of clusters.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Using the training data compute the mean (*μ**ℓ**i*) and variance (σ*ℓ**i*) for each label.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Compute the marginal distribution for the given labeling scheme *P*(*fi* | *ℓ**i*) using Bayes' theorem and the class statistics calculated earlier.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Calculate the probability of each class label given the neighborhood defined previously.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Clique potentials are used to model the social impact in labeling.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Iterate over new prior probabilities and redefine clusters such that these probabilities are maximized.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] This is done using a variety of optimization algorithms described below.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Stop when probability is maximized and labeling scheme does not change.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The calculations can be implemented in log likelihood terms as well.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Each optimization algorithm is an adaptation of models from a variety of fields and they are set apart by their unique cost functions.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The common trait of cost functions is to penalize change in pixel value as well as difference in pixel label when compared to labels of neighboring pixels.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] where α is the penalty for change in pixel label and β is the penalty for difference in label between neighboring pixels and chosen pixel.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Here $N(i)$ is neighborhood of pixel i and δ is the Kronecker delta function.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] A major issue with ICM is that, similar to gradient descent, it has a tendency to rest over local maxima and thus not obtain a globally optimal labeling scheme.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Derived as an analogue of annealing in metallurgy, simulated annealing (SA) uses change in pixel label over iterations and estimates the difference in energy of each newly formed graph to the initial data.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] the algorithm selects the newly formed graph.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Simulated annealing requires the input of temperature schedules which directly affects the speed of convergence of the system, as well as energy threshold for minimization to occur.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] A range of other methods exist for solving simple as well as higher order MRFs.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] They include Maximization of Posterior Marginal, Multi-scale MAP estimation, Multiple Resolution segmentation and more.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Apart from likelihood estimates, graph-cut using maximum flow and other highly constrained graph based methods exist for solving MRFs.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The expectation–maximization algorithm is utilized to iteratively estimate the a posterior probabilities and distributions of labeling when no training data is available and no estimate of segmentation model can be formed.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] E step: Estimate class statistics based on the random segmentation model defined.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Using these, compute the conditional probability of belonging to a label given the feature set is calculated using naive Bayes' theorem.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Here $\lambda \in \Lambda$ , the set of all possible labels.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] M step: The established relevance of a given feature set to a labeling scheme is now used to compute the a priori estimate of a given label in the second part of the algorithm.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Since the actual number of total labels is unknown (from a training data set), a hidden estimate of the number of labels given by the user is utilized in computations.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] where $\Omega$ is the set of all possible features.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Approximate MAP estimates are computationally expensive to calculate.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Extension to multi-class labeling degrades performance and increases storage required.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Reliable estimation of parameters for EM is required for global optima to be achieved.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Based on method of optimization, segmentation may cluster to local minima.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The watershed transformation considers the gradient magnitude of an image as a topographic surface.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Pixels having the highest gradient magnitude intensities (GMIs) correspond to watershed lines, which represent the region boundaries.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Water placed on any pixel enclosed by a common watershed line flows downhill to a common local intensity minimum (LIM).
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Pixels draining to a common minimum form a catch basin, which represents a segment.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The central assumption of model-based approaches is that the structures of interest have a tendency towards a particular shape.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Therefore, one can seek a probabilistic model that characterizes the shape and its variation.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] When segmenting an image, constraints can be imposed using this model as a prior.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Such a task may involve (i) registration of the training examples to a common pose, (ii) probabilistic representation of the variation of the registered samples, and (iii) statistical inference between the model and the image.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Other important methods in the literature for model-based segmentation include active shape models and active appearance models.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Image segmentations are computed at multiple scales in scale space and sometimes propagated from coarse to fine scales; see scale-space segmentation.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Segmentation criteria can be arbitrarily complex and may take into account global as well as local criteria.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] A common requirement is that each region must be connected in some sense.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Witkin's seminal work in scale space included the notion that a one-dimensional signal could be unambiguously segmented into regions, with one scale parameter controlling the scale of segmentation.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] A key observation is that the zero-crossings of the second derivatives (minima and maxima of the first derivative or slope) of multi-scale-smoothed versions of a signal form a nesting tree, which defines hierarchical relations between segments at different scales.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Specifically, slope extrema at coarse scales can be traced back to corresponding features at fine scales.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] When a slope maximum and slope minimum annihilate each other at a larger scale, the three segments that they separated merge into one segment, thus defining the hierarchy of segments.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] There have been numerous research works in this area, out of which a few have now reached a state where they can be applied either with interactive manual intervention (usually with application to medical imaging) or fully automatically.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The following is a brief overview of some of the main research ideas that current approaches are based upon.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The nesting structure that Witkin described is, however, specific for one-dimensional signals and does not trivially transfer to higher-dimensional images.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Nevertheless, this general idea has inspired several other authors to investigate coarse-to-fine schemes for image segmentation.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Koenderink proposed to study how iso-intensity contours evolve over scales and this approach was investigated in more detail by Lifshitz and Pizer.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Unfortunately, however, the intensity of image features changes over scales, which implies that it is hard to trace coarse-scale image features to finer scales using iso-intensity information.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Bergholm proposed to detect edges at coarse scales in scale-space and then trace them back to finer scales with manual choice of both the coarse detection scale and the fine localization scale.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Gauch and Pizer studied the complementary problem of ridges and valleys at multiple scales and developed a tool for interactive image segmentation based on multi-scale watersheds.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The use of multi-scale watershed with application to the gradient map has also been investigated by Olsen and Nielsen and been carried over to clinical use by Dam.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Vincken et al. proposed a hyperstack for defining probabilistic relations between image structures at different scales.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The use of stable image structures over scales has been furthered by Ahuja and his co-workers into a fully automated system.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] A fully automatic brain segmentation algorithm based on closely related ideas of multi-scale watersheds has been presented by Undeman and Lindeberg and been extensively tested in brain databases.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] These ideas for multi-scale image segmentation by linking image structures over scales have also been picked up by Florack and Kuijper.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Bijaoui and Rué associate structures detected in scale-space above a minimum noise threshold into an object tree which spans multiple scales and corresponds to a kind of feature in the original signal.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Extracted features are accurately reconstructed using an iterative conjugate gradient matrix method.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] In one kind of segmentation, the user outlines the region of interest with the mouse clicks and algorithms are applied so that the path that best fits the edge of the image is shown.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Techniques like SIOX, Livewire, Intelligent Scissors or IT-SNAPS are used in this kind of segmentation.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] In an alternative kind of semi-automatic segmentation, the algorithms return a spatial-taxon (i.e. foreground, object-group, object or object-part) selected by the user or designated via prior probabilities.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Most of the aforementioned segmentation methods are based only on color information of pixels in the image.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Humans use much more knowledge when performing image segmentation, but implementing this knowledge would cost considerable human engineering and computational time, and would require a huge domain knowledge database which does not currently exist.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Trainable segmentation methods, such as neural network segmentation, overcome these issues by modeling the domain knowledge from a dataset of labeled pixels.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] An image segmentation neural network can process small areas of an image to extract simple features such as edges.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Another neural network, or any decision-making mechanism, can then combine these features to label the areas of an image accordingly.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] A type of network designed this way is the Kohonen map.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Pulse-coupled neural networks (PCNNs) are neural models proposed by modeling a cat's visual cortex and developed for high-performance biomimetic image processing.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] In 1989, Reinhard Eckhorn introduced a neural model to emulate the mechanism of a cat's visual cortex.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The Eckhorn model provided a simple and effective tool for studying the visual cortex of small mammals, and was soon recognized as having significant application potential in image processing.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] In 1994, the Eckhorn model was adapted to be an image processing algorithm by John L.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Johnson, who termed this algorithm Pulse-Coupled Neural Network.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Over the past decade, PCNNs have been utilized for a variety of image processing applications, including: image segmentation, feature generation, face extraction, motion detection, region growing, noise reduction, and so on.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] A PCNN is a two-dimensional neural network.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Each neuron in the network corresponds to one pixel in an input image, receiving its corresponding pixel's color information (e.g. intensity) as an external stimulus.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Each neuron also connects with its neighboring neurons, receiving local stimuli from them.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The external and local stimuli are combined in an internal activation system, which accumulates the stimuli until it exceeds a dynamic threshold, resulting in a pulse output.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Through iterative computation, PCNN neurons produce temporal series of pulse outputs.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The temporal series of pulse outputs contain information of input images and can be utilized for various image processing applications, such as image segmentation and feature generation.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Compared with conventional image processing means, PCNNs have several significant merits, including robustness against noise, independence of geometric variations in input patterns, capability of bridging minor intensity variations in input patterns, etc.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] In 2015, convolutional neural networks reached state of the art in semantic segmentation.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] U-Net is an architecture which takes as input an image and outputs a label for each pixel.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] U-Net initially was developed to detect cell boundaries in biomedical images.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] U-Net follows classical autoencoder architecture, as such it contains two sub-structures.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The encoder structure follows the traditional stack of convolutional and max pooling layers to increase the receptive field as it goes through the layers.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] It is used to capture the context in the image.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The decoder structure utilizes transposed convolution layers for upsampling so that the end dimensions are close to that of the input image.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Skip connections are placed between convolution and transposed convolution layers of the same shape in order to preserve details that would have been lost otherwise.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Related images such as a photo album or a sequence of video frames often contain semantically similar objects and scenes, therefore it is often beneficial to exploit such correlations.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] The task of simultaneously segmenting scenes from related images or video frames is termed co-segmentation, which is typically used in human action localization.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Unlike conventional bounding box-based object detection, human action localization methods provide finer-grained results, typically per-image segmentation masks delineating the human object of interest and its action category (e.g., *Segment-Tube*).
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] Techniques such as dynamic Markov Networks, CNN and LSTM are often employed to exploit the inter-frame correlations.
[src:optical-character-recognition/image-segmentation] There are many other methods of segmentation like multispectral segmentation or connectivity-based segmentation based on DTI images.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] OCR is a field of research in pattern recognition, artificial intelligence and computer vision.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] Early versions needed to be trained with images of each character, and worked on one font at a time.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] Advanced systems capable of producing a high degree of accuracy for most fonts are now common, and with support for a variety of image file format inputs.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] Some systems are capable of reproducing formatted output that closely approximates the original page including images, columns, and other non-textual components.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] Early optical character recognition may be traced to technologies involving telegraphy and creating reading devices for the blind.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] In 1914, Emanuel Goldberg developed a machine that read characters and converted them into standard telegraph code.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] Concurrently, Edmund Fournier d'Albe developed the Optophone, a handheld scanner that when moved across a printed page, produced tones that corresponded to specific letters or characters.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] In the late 1920s and into the 1930s, Emanuel Goldberg developed what he called a "Statistical Machine" for searching microfilm archives using an optical code recognition system.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] In 1931, he was granted US Patent number 1,838,389 for the invention.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] In 1974, Ray Kurzweil started the company Kurzweil Computer Products, Inc. and continued development of omni-font OCR, which could recognize text printed in virtually any font.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] (Kurzweil is often credited with inventing omni-font OCR, but it was in use by companies, including CompuScan, in the late 1960s and 1970s.) Kurzweil used the technology to create a reading machine for blind people to have a computer read text to them out loud.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] The device included a CCD-type flatbed scanner and a text-to-speech synthesizer.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] On January 13, 1976, the finished product was unveiled during a widely reported news conference headed by Kurzweil and the leaders of the National Federation of the Blind.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] In 1978, Kurzweil Computer Products began selling a commercial version of the optical character recognition computer program.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] LexisNexis was one of the first customers, and bought the program to upload legal paper and news documents onto its nascent online databases.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] Two years later, Kurzweil sold his company to Xerox, which eventually spun it off as Scansoft, which merged with Nuance Communications.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] In the 2000s, OCR was made available online as a service (WebOCR), in a cloud computing environment, and in mobile applications like real-time translation of foreign-language signs on a smartphone.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] With the advent of smartphones and smartglasses, OCR can be used in internet connected mobile device applications that extract text captured using the device's camera.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] These devices that do not have built-in OCR functionality will typically use an OCR API to extract the text from the image file captured by the device.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] The OCR API returns the extracted text, along with information about the location of the detected text in the original image back to the device app for further processing (such as text-to-speech) or display.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] Various commercial and open source OCR systems are available for most common writing systems, including Latin, Cyrillic, Arabic, Hebrew, Indic, Bengali (Bangla), Devanagari, Tamil, Chinese, Japanese, and Korean characters.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] OCR engines have been developed into software applications specializing in various subjects such as receipts, invoices, checks, and legal billing documents.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] OCR is generally an offline process, which analyses a static document.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] There are cloud based services which provide an online OCR API service.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] Handwriting movement analysis can be used as input to handwriting recognition.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] Instead of merely using the shapes of glyphs and words, this technique is able to capture motion, such as the order in which segments are drawn, the direction, and the pattern of putting the pen down and lifting it.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] This additional information can make the process more accurate.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] This technology is also known as "online character recognition", "dynamic character recognition", "real-time character recognition", and "intelligent character recognition".
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] OCR software often pre-processes images to improve the chances of successful recognition.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] Segmentation of fixed-pitch fonts is accomplished relatively simply by aligning the image to a uniform grid based on where vertical grid lines will least often intersect black areas.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] For proportional fonts, more sophisticated techniques are needed because whitespace between letters can sometimes be greater than that between words, and vertical lines can intersect more than one character.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] There are two basic types of core OCR algorithm, which may produce a ranked list of candidate characters.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] Software such as Cuneiform and Tesseract use a two-pass approach to character recognition.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] The second pass is known as adaptive recognition and uses the letter shapes recognized with high confidence on the first pass to better recognize the remaining letters on the second pass.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] This is advantageous for unusual fonts or low-quality scans where the font is distorted (e.g. blurred or faded).
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] Others like OCRopus and Tesseract use neural networks which are trained to recognize whole lines of text instead of focusing on single characters.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] A technique known as iterative OCR automatically crops a document into sections based on the page layout.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] OCR is then performed on each section individually using variable character confidence level thresholds to maximize page-level OCR accuracy.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] A patent from the United States Patent Office has been issued for this method.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] The OCR result can be stored in the standardized ALTO format, a dedicated XML schema maintained by the United States Library of Congress.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] Other common formats include hOCR and PAGE XML.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] For a list of optical character recognition software, see Comparison of optical character recognition software.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] OCR accuracy can be increased if the output is constrained by a lexicon – a list of words that are allowed to occur in a document.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] This might be, for example, all the words in the English language, or a more technical lexicon for a specific field.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] This technique can be problematic if the document contains words not in the lexicon, like proper nouns.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] Tesseract uses its dictionary to influence the character segmentation step, for improved accuracy.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] The output stream may be a plain text stream or file of characters, but more sophisticated OCR systems can preserve the original layout of the page and produce, for example, an annotated PDF that includes both the original image of the page and a searchable textual representation.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] Knowledge of the grammar of the language being scanned can also help determine if a word is likely to be a verb or a noun, for example, allowing greater accuracy.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] The Levenshtein Distance algorithm has also been used in OCR post-processing to further optimize results from an OCR API.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] In recent years, the major OCR technology providers began to tweak OCR systems to deal more efficiently with specific types of input.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] Beyond an application-specific lexicon, better performance may be had by taking into account business rules, standard expression, or rich information contained in color images.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] This strategy is called "Application-Oriented OCR" or "Customized OCR", and has been applied to OCR of license plates, invoices, screenshots, ID cards, driver's licenses, and automobile manufacturing.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] There are several techniques for solving the problem of character recognition by means other than improved OCR algorithms.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] Special fonts like OCR-A, OCR-B, or MICR fonts, with precisely specified sizing, spacing, and distinctive character shapes, allow a higher accuracy rate during transcription in bank check processing.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] Several prominent OCR engines were designed to capture text in popular fonts such as Arial or Times New Roman, and are incapable of capturing text in these fonts that are specialized and very different from popularly used fonts.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] As Google Tesseract can be trained to recognize new fonts, it can recognize OCR-A, OCR-B and MICR fonts.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] Palm OS used a special set of glyphs, known as Graffiti, which are similar to printed English characters but simplified or modified for easier recognition on the platform's computationally limited hardware.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] Users would need to learn how to write these special glyphs.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] Zone-based OCR restricts the image to a specific part of a document.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] This is often referred to as *Template OCR*.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] Crowdsourcing humans to perform the character recognition can quickly process images like computer-driven OCR, but with higher accuracy for recognizing images than that obtained via computers.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] Practical systems include the Amazon Mechanical Turk and reCAPTCHA.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] The National Library of Finland has developed an online interface for users to correct OCRed texts in the standardized ALTO format.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] Crowd sourcing has also been used not to perform character recognition directly but to invite software developers to develop image processing algorithms, for example, through the use of rank-order tournaments.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] Department of Energy (DOE), the Information Science Research Institute (ISRI) had the mission to foster the improvement of automated technologies for understanding machine printed documents, and it conducted the most authoritative of the *Annual Test of OCR Accuracy* from 1992 to 1996.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] Recognition of typewritten, Latin script text is still not 100% accurate even where clear imaging is available.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] One study based on recognition of 19th- and early 20th-century newspaper pages concluded that character-by-character OCR accuracy for commercial OCR software varied from 81% to 99%; total accuracy can be achieved by human review or Data Dictionary Authentication.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] Other areas – including recognition of hand printing, cursive handwriting, and printed text in other scripts (especially those East Asian language characters which have many strokes for a single character) – are still the subject of active research.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] The MNIST database is commonly used for testing systems' ability to recognize handwritten digits.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] Accuracy rates can be measured in several ways, and how they are measured can greatly affect the reported accuracy rate.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] For example, if word context (a lexicon of words) is not used to correct software finding non-existent words, a character error rate of 1% (99% accuracy) may result in an error rate of 5% or worse if the measurement is based on whether each whole word was recognized with no incorrect letters.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] Using a large enough dataset is important in a neural-network-based handwriting recognition solutions.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] On the other hand, producing natural datasets is very complicated and time-consuming.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] An example of the difficulties inherent in digitizing old text is the inability of OCR to differentiate between the "long s" and "f" characters.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] Recognition of cursive text has recognition rates even lower than that of hand-printed text.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] Higher rates of recognition of general cursive script will likely not be possible without the use of contextual or grammatical information.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] For example, recognizing entire words from a dictionary is easier than trying to parse individual characters from script.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] Reading the *Amount* line of a check (which is always a written-out number) is an example where using a smaller dictionary can increase recognition rates greatly.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] The shapes of individual cursive characters themselves simply do not contain enough information to accurately (greater than 98%) recognize all handwritten cursive script.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] Most programs allow users to set "confidence rates".
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] This means that if the software does not achieve their desired level of accuracy, a user can be notified for manual review.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] An error introduced by OCR scanning is sometimes termed a *scanno* (by analogy with the term *typo*).
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] Characters to support OCR were added to the Unicode Standard in June 1993, with the release of version 1.1.
[src:optical-character-recognition/optical-character-recognition] Some of these characters are mapped from fonts specific to MICR, OCR-A or OCR-B.
